result.summary: This function removes duplicate elements from a list while preserving the original order of the first occurrence of each element.

best.description: Best case occurs when all elements are unique, and the 'in' check on 'result' is O(1) on average for hashable types. However, since 'result' is a list, the 'in' check is O(k) where k is the current size of result. Thus, the loop becomes O(1 + 2 + ... + n) = O(n^2). If 'result' were a set, this would be O(n).

average.description: On average, each 'item in result' check takes time proportional to the current size of 'result', leading to a quadratic time complexity.

worst.description: In the worst case, where many duplicates exist or the list is large, the 'item in result' check dominates, resulting in quadratic time complexity.

spaceComplexity.description: The space complexity is O(n) because a new list 'result' is created, which can store up to n unique elements in the worst case.

issues.title: Inefficient duplicate checking
issues.description: The 'item not in result' check on a list has a time complexity of O(k), where k is the current number of elements in 'result'. This leads to an overall O(n^2) time complexity for the function. Using a set for checking membership would improve performance significantly.
